title: SAIC signs another commercial partner for its small satellite business
summary: U.S. defense contractor SAIC announced May 5 it will partner with European manufacturer GomSpace to develop small satellites for U.S. government agencies, commercial firms and universities.

title: US, Russian EVAs install upgrades and make history aboard ISS
summary: NASA and Roscosmos astronauts have both conducted spacewalks this week aboard the International Space Station (ISS). The spacewalks prepared the Station for additional iROSA panel installation activity later this summer, added a long-awaited airlock to the Nauka science module, and made history with the first citizen of an Arab country to conduct an EVA.

title: NASA Invites Media to Next SpaceX Resupply Launch to Space Station
summary: Media accreditation is open for SpaceX’s 28th commercial resupply mission for NASA to the International Space Station. Liftoff of the SpaceX Dragon cargo spacecraft on the company’s Falcon 9 rocket is targeted no earlier than 12:34 p.m. EDT Saturday, June 3, from Launch Complex 39A at NASA’s Kennedy Space Center in Florida.

title: NASA, Rocket Lab Update Launch Coverage for Tropical Cyclones Mission
summary: After the previous launch target date changed due to weather conditions in New Zealand, NASA and Rocket Lab are now targeting 9 p.m. EDT Sunday, May 7, (1 p.m. Monday, May 8, New Zealand Standard Time), to launch two storm tracking CubeSats into orbit

title: Scientists say they have found more moons with oceans in the Solar System
summary: NASA probably is about to get serious about exploring the Uranian system.

title: DoD spending on commercial space services negligible, despite growing Space Force budget
summary: Pentagon officials have called attention to DoD’s need to access commercial space industry services. However, very little of the Space Force’s budget is being allocated to these types of services, analyst Mike Tierney said May 2.

title: Society and Technology: The Space Observing Imperative
summary: Scientific spacecraft programs are too important to the United States' welfare and our leadership in the world to ever shortchange or undervalue them through poor policy decisions

title: BlackSky seeks to extend operations of satellites running on empty
summary: BlackSky is requesting permission to operate two of its satellites in lower orbits as the spacecraft are running out of propellant.

title: Rocket Report: China selling reusable engines; can SpaceX still raise money?
summary: "We all know that China and Russia and others have been doing lots of flights."

title: Orbex Breaks Ground On UK Mainland's First Vertical Launch Facility
summary: Orbex, a UK-based rocket service provider for small satellites, has begun the construction of the first vertical launch spaceport on the UK mainland, located on the North coast of Scotland.
